UK DQ Assessment control development

Please find below the specific examples of DQ assessment controls we would expect the UK to develop.


________________________________________
Business Consistency checks (Perimeter validation / exposure eligibility) — UK FIRB Corporates Other/SME
Perimeter validation: “Corporates Other/SME FIRB Approach: non-specialised trading companies based in the UK that do not fall under the Global Corporate Model perimeter (defined as turnover ≥ £500m).”
BC-01 — Explicit exclusion of Global Corporate Model by Turnover
•	Rule: If Turnover ≥ 500m GBP, the record should not be included in the FIRB Corporates Other/SME RDS (or should be clearly marked as non-eligible).
•	Fields: Turnover, Segment, Portfolio.
•	Outputs / evidence:
o	% of RDS records with Turnover ≥ 500m (expected to be ~0).
o	Exception list with reason codes (if any).
•	Clarification to confirm: Can you confirm Turnover is always in GBP (or otherwise how currency/unit standardisation is ensured)?
________________________________________
BC-02 — Inclusion control: eligible records should not be unintentionally excluded
•	Rule: Records with Turnover < 500m and Portfolio/Segment aligned to the approved FIRB Corporates Other/SME scope should not be excluded from the RDS unless there is a documented exclusion reason.
•	Fields: Turnover, Portfolio, Segment, Borrower_ID, Date.
•	Outputs / evidence:
o	Monthly coverage ratio = (# records in RDS)/(# eligible records in local systems).
o	Breakdown of excluded eligible records by reason (if applicable).
________________________________________
BC-03 — UK geography validation (UK-based perimeter)
•	Rule: All RDS records should satisfy the agreed “UK-based” definition
•	Fields needed: We do not see any “Country”-like fields in the data dictionary. How has this perimeter been calculated? Typically something like country, booking_country, incorporation_country, or equivalent would be used.
•	Outputs / evidence:
o	% records failing UK geography rule (expected to be 0 or fully explained).
•	Clarification to confirm: Which field(s) are being used to evidence “UK-based”, and are they already present in the perimeter extract / RDS? If not, what is the agreed proxy to demonstrate UK scope?
________________________________________
BC-04 — Sector eligibility: exclude non-applicable sectors (e.g., financials / holdings), if required by scope
•	Rule (to confirm with Methodology): If Internal_sector indicates sectors outside “non-specialised trading companies” (e.g., financial sector or holding-type sectors), those records should be excluded or handled under explicit exceptions.
•	Fields: Internal_sector, Portfolio, Segment.
•	Outputs / evidence:
o	List of “out-of-scope” sector codes present in the RDS (if any), with justification.
•	Clarification to confirm: Do you have an approved sector → eligibility mapping (reference table) that defines which Internal_sector values are in/out of scope?
________________________________________
BC-05 — Non-specialised vs specialised lending / product eligibility (where applicable)
•	Rule: Exposures that fall under specialised lending / non-trading definitions (as per scope) should be excluded, or explicitly flagged for separate treatment.
•	Fields typically required: We do not see any fields such as exposure_class, product_type, specialised_lending_flag, counterparty_type (or equivalents). We assume they were probably used in the extraction itself, but could you please confirm what fields did you use to determine the perimeter?
•	Outputs / evidence:
o	% of records meeting specialised/out-of-scope criteria that appear in the RDS.
•	Clarification to confirm: Which fields are being used to identify specialised lending / product eligibility, and are they already present in the data extracted for the RDS build?
________________________________________
BC-06 — (recommendation to make the perimeter defensible) Minimum perimeter audit fields
To make Business Consistency evidence robust (especially for supervision), it is typically helpful that the RDS/perimeter extract contains:
•	eligibility_flag (Y/N)
•	exclusion_reason (closed list of codes)
Completeness Checks – Validation of Data Completeness, Coverage, and Representativeness (UK)

Perimeter: Final RDS population for the FIRB Corporates Other / SME UK model
________________________________________
C-01 — Functional completeness for all RDS variables
•	Rule: For each variable in the Data Dictionary, compute the percentage of missing (null or equivalent) values by month over the full observation window.
•	Applies to: All variables (identifiers, segmentation drivers, financial, behavioural, bureau, qualitative).
•	Outputs / evidence:
o	Monthly missingness per variable (%).
o	Identification of variables with persistent or structurally high missingness.
For variables with non-negligible missingness, can you confirm whether:
o	Missing values are structural/expected (e.g. not applicable by design, new borrower, etc.), or
o	Missing values indicate data availability or ingestion gaps?
________________________________________
C-02 — Identification and governance of “equivalent missing” values
•	Rule: Identify values that technically exist but functionally behave as missing (e.g. zeros, default technical codes, extreme placeholders).
•	Applies to: Numeric variables (ratios, balances, arrears metrics), categorical encoders, qualitative scores.
•	Outputs / evidence:
o	List of equivalent-missing patterns per variable (e.g. 0, -999, extreme constants).
o	% incidence by month.
•	Recommendation:
For auditing purposes, it would be helpful if there was a documented rule defining which values are treated as “equivalent to missing” for each variable, and how they are handled downstream (binning, imputation, neutral category)?
________________________________________
C-03 — Historical completeness across the full modelling window
•	Rule: For each variable, verify the first and last available observation date and compare it with the required historical depth for a given model.
•	Applies to: All variables.
•	Outputs / evidence:
o	Coverage “matrix”: variable × month.
o	Explicit identification of start dates later than “X” (depends on Rating or PD data).
•	Clarification to confirm:
For variables with shorter history:
o	Is the reduced depth intentional and accepted by Methodology?
o	Are these variables excluded from development periods where history is insufficient, or is a proxy/alternative used?
________________________________________
This check is not mandatory since it can be directly evaluated in the historical completeness, but this view might be helpful to ensure targeted Remediation Plans if needed.
C-04 — Completeness stability over time (temporal consistency)
•	Rule: Assess whether missingness levels are stable over time or show structural breaks (sudden improvements/deteriorations).
•	Applies to: All variables, with particular focus on financial ratios, behavioural aggregates, and bureau data.
•	Outputs / evidence:
o	Time series of missingness % per variable.
o	Flags for sudden step-changes.
•	Clarification to confirm:
Where step-changes are observed, can you confirm whether these correspond to known events (system changes, new feeds, methodology updates), and are these changes documented?
________________________________________
This check is not mandatory but it might be helpful to ensure targeted Remediation Plans if needed.
C-05 — Completeness by segment and borrower characteristics
•	Rule: Evaluate missingness by key segmentation dimensions to detect representativeness bias.
•	Dimensions to test (at minimum):
o	Segment
o	Internal_sector
o	Turnover bands
o	Exposure size bands (Total_Exposure)
o	Rating band (if available)
•	Applies to: Key financial, behavioural, bureau, and qualitative drivers.
•	Outputs / evidence:
o	Missingness % by segment/dimension.
o	Identification of asymmetric patterns (e.g. small corporates systematically missing financials).
•	Clarification to confirm:
If completeness differs materially by segment, is this:
o	Expected by design (e.g. simplified data for smaller firms), or
o	A potential source of bias that requires mitigation or documentation?
________________________________________
C-06 — Completeness of segmentation and governance drivers
•	Rule: Variables used to define or evidence the model perimeter must be near-complete.
•	Critical fields include: Turnover, Portfolio, Segment, Internal_sector, Borrower_ID, Date.
•	Outputs / evidence:
o	Missingness % for each segmentation driver.
•	Clarification to confirm:
How are cases handled where segmentation drivers are missing or inconsistent? Is there a fallback rule, and is it formally documented?
________________________________________
C-07 — Coverage of the eligible population in the RDS
•	Rule: Quantify how much of the eligible population is ultimately represented in the RDS.
•	Metrics:
o	% of eligible borrowers included (count).
o	% of eligible exposure included (Total_Exposure).
•	Outputs / evidence:
o	Monthly coverage ratios.
o	Trend over time.
•	Clarification to confirm:
Are exclusions driven mainly by missing critical variables, explicit business rules, or technical constraints? Is this split visible and auditable?
________________________________________
C-08 — Completeness of derived variables vs input availability
•	Rule: For calculated variables (MA, YOY, ratios), assess whether missingness is driven by:
o	Missing inputs, or
o	Insufficient historical depth.
•	Applies to: MA_* and YOY_* variables, behavioural aggregates.
•	Outputs / evidence:
o	Comparison of missingness between inputs and derived outputs.
•	Clarification to confirm:
Is there a minimum-history rule (e.g. at least 2 financial statements) that governs calculation, and is this consistently applied and documented?
________________________________________
C-09 — Flags to govern completeness-related exclusions and adjustments
•	Rule: Ensure the RDS includes governance fields to track completeness-driven actions.
•	Expected fields (or equivalents):
o	data_quality_flag
o	exclusion_flag
o	exclusion_reason
o	adjustment_flag
•	Outputs / evidence:
o	Confirmation of field availability and usage.
•	Clarification to confirm:
If such flags are not currently available, how is completeness-driven exclusion or adjustment evidenced during validation or supervision?
________________________________________
If you want, the next step could be:
•	translating these into quantitative thresholds and severity levels, or
•	mapping each check to specific variable families (financial, behavioural, bureau, qualitative) with expected outcomes for Cycle 1 vs Cycle 2.
