Internal Consistency Checks (UK) — Logical Cross-Field Validation
Perimeter: Final RDS population (one record per Borrower_ID per Date)
Objective: Detect internal contradictions between key fields (defaults, arrears/DPD, behavioural histories, segmentation, exposures, financial ratios), ensuring the dataset is logically coherent and defensible under internal validation / supervisory review.
________________________________________
1) Record-key integrity (prerequisite for all internal checks)
IC-01 — Uniqueness of borrower-month
•	Rule: One and only one record per (Borrower_ID, Date)
•	Why: Any duplicated borrower-month breaks behavioural derivations and can double-count exposures/defaults.
•	Check: count(*) grouped by (Borrower_ID,Date) must be 1.
IC-02 — Time continuity (optional but strongly recommended)
•	Rule: For each Borrower_ID, Date should progress monthly without “future” backfills inside the same extract.
•	Why: Behavioural “months since” and consecutive metrics assume correct month ordering.
•	Check: gaps in Date sequence for borrowers with behavioural variables populated.
________________________________________
2) Default / NPL flags vs behavioural delinquency (DPD / arrears)
IC-03 — Default should be compatible with delinquency signals
•	Rule (conditional): If Default = 1, then at least one of:
o	DPD > 0, or
o	Arrears > 0, or
o	wo_npl=1, np_npl=1, dr_npl=1, su_npl(1/2/3)=1, ff_npl=1
•	Why: Default typically coincides with arrears/NPL-type flags (unless there is a pure UTP / subjective default pathway). This check identifies defaults that look “unexplained”.
•	Exception: If the UK framework allows Default=1 via UTP with DPD=0 and Arrears=0, this must be explicitly documented; otherwise it will look like a data mapping issue.

IC-04 — No delinquency history but DPD > 0
•	Rule: If DPD > 0 then MonthsSince_DPDGT0 must be 0 (or a defined technical representation of “current month event”).
•	Why: If borrower is currently delinquent, “months since DPD >0” cannot be non-zero or missing (unless the variable definition differs).
•	Check: DPD>0 AND MonthsSince_DPDGT0 NOT IN (0, allowed_codes).
IC-05 — Arrears amount should align with DPD
•	Rule (conditional):
o	If Arrears > 0, then DPD > 0 is generally expected.
•	Why: Positive arrears typically implies late payment days >0. Violations may point to arrears currency issues, timing misalignment, or incorrect DPD derivation.
•	Exception: If arrears are defined “at month end” while DPD is “at due date”, this could legitimately occur but should be documented.
IC-06 — If DPD = 0, arrears-based “consecutive arrears” should be 0
•	Rule: If DPD = 0 and Arrears = 0, then:
o	Consec_ArrGT0 = 0
o	Consec_ArrGT30/60/90 = 0
•	Why: Consecutive arrears counters should not show ongoing delinquency if current month is clean.
•	Exception: If those counters are computed on a window ending at prior month, then they should be consistent with that definition (needs explicit confirmation).
________________________________________
3) “MonthsSince_*” variables vs threshold indicators

IC-07 — Ordering constraints between thresholds
•	Rule: MonthsSince_DPDGT90 ≥ MonthsSince_DPDGT60 ≥ MonthsSince_DPDGT30 ≥ MonthsSince_DPDGT0
•	Reason: It’s easier to have been delinquent >0 than >30, etc. In principle, a more severe threshold cannot be “more recent” unless definitions differ.
•	Exception: If each MonthsSince variable is computed from independent event definitions, then UK should document that (otherwise supervisors will expect monotonicity).
IC-08 — “Months since DPD>30” cannot be 0 if DPD is below threshold
•	Rule: If DPD <= 30, then MonthsSince_DPDGT30 cannot be 0 (it should be >0 or missing depending on meaning).
•	Why: Zero implies “this month had DPD >30”.
•	Check: DPD<=30 AND MonthsSince_DPDGT30=0.
IC-09 — MonthsSince_MaxArr vs MaxArr values
•	Rule (conditional): If MonthsSince_MaxArr = 0, then current arrears should be equal to the “max arrears to date” metric (MaxArr_ALL) or at least equal to the max observed in the window that defines it.
•	Why: “Months since max arrears” being 0 means this month is the max event.
•	Note: Because you have multiple max definitions (3m/6m/12m/ALL), UK should specify which one MonthsSince_MaxArr relates to.
________________________________________
4) Behavioural min/max/avg variables vs base balances/arrears
IC-10 — Balance must lie within min/max window when window exists
•	Rule: If MinBal_3m and MaxBal_3m are populated then:
o	MinBal_3m ≤ Balance ≤ MaxBal_3m
•	Why: If not, the rolling window stats are inconsistent with the underlying balance series.
•	Apply similarly for 6m, 12m, ALL.
IC-11 — Arrears must lie within min/max window when window exists
•	Rule: If MinArr_3m and MaxArr_3m are populated then:
o	MinArr_3m ≤ Arrears ≤ MaxArr_3m
•	Why: Same as above; detects misalignment in window calculation.
IC-12 — Max/Min hierarchy across windows
•	Rule (conditional):
o	MaxBal_ALL ≥ MaxBal_12m ≥ MaxBal_6m ≥ MaxBal_3m
o	MinBal_ALL ≤ MinBal_ALL(12m) ≤ MinBal_6m ≤ MinBal_3m (depending on how “ALL” is defined; if ALL=12m then align accordingly)
•	Why: Wider windows should not have smaller maxima / larger minima unless “ALL” is not actually longer.
•	Action: If UK defines ALL as “to date” and not capped, this should hold. If ALL is 12m, then naming should be clarified.
IC-13 — Percent-of-months vs counts consistency
•	Rule: For a 12m window:
o	Count_ArrGT30_12m ≈ round(PCT_ArrGT30_12m * 12 / 100) (allow tolerance of ±1 due to rounding)
•	Why: These are two views of the same concept. Large mismatches imply inconsistent windowing or scaling (0–1 vs 0–100).
•	Apply similarly for GT0/GT60/GT90 and 3m/6m.
________________________________________
5) Behavioural deltas and consecutive metrics vs actual month-on-month changes
IC-14 — Increase/Decrease variables should not both be positive
•	Rule: For balances:
o	Not allowed: Increase_In_Bal > 0 AND Decrease_In_Bal > 0 in the same record.
o	Additionally: if Increase_In_Bal > 0 then Decrease_In_Bal should be 0 (or missing), and vice versa.
•	Why: A value can’t increase and decrease simultaneously; flags derivation logic bugs.
IC-15 — Same logic for arrears
•	Rule: Not allowed: Increase_In_Arr > 0 AND Decrease_In_Arr > 0
•	Why: Same as above.
IC-16 — Consecutive counters vs “no change”
•	Rule: If ConsecNoChge_Arr > 0, then Increase_In_Arr = 0 and Decrease_In_Arr = 0 should be expected.
•	Why: “No change” counters should align with delta fields.
________________________________________
6) Exposure, group exposure, and grouping logic
IC-17 — Group exposure should be coherent with individual exposure
•	Rule (conditional): If GROUP_CODE is populated, then final_group_expsr ≥ Total_Exposure
•	Why: Group exposure should be at least as large as a member exposure.
•	Exception: If final_group_expsr is “allocated” rather than aggregated, UK should document that (otherwise this is a red flag).
IC-18 — If GROUP_CODE is null, group exposure should be null or equal to borrower exposure
•	Rule: If GROUP_CODE is null/empty, then final_group_expsr should be null or equal to Total_Exposure (depending on design).
•	Why: Avoids accidental carryover of group values to standalone borrowers.
________________________________________
7) Segment / Portfolio vs variable applicability (structural consistency)
These are “internal consistency” in the sense of structural applicability across fields.
IC-19 — Qualitative block applicability vs Segment
•	Rule (conditional): If Segment/Portfolio indicates SME questionnaire is required, then SMEQL_RQS_* should not be null (or should follow the documented defaulting logic).
•	Why: Prevents silent dilution of the qualitative block due to missingness driven by process gaps rather than “true neutral”.
IC-20 — Financial ratio families should align with portfolio assignment
•	Rule (conditional):
o	If a borrower is tagged as SME model population, SME ratio set should be present and GC/CCT may be irrelevant (or vice versa).
•	Why: Prevents mixing submodel drivers due to incorrect portfolio mapping.
•	Note: UK will need to confirm which portfolio uses GC vs CCT vs SME vs CCB—if this mapping is not available in the current dataset, it is a gap (a segmentation driver or model_id flag may be needed).
________________________________________
8) Financial ratio cross-checks (limited without raw inputs)
Because the RDS contains ratios but not the underlying statement line items, internal checks are necessarily lighter, but still possible.
IC-21 — Duplicate ratio definitions should not diverge materially
•	Rule: SME_Ratio_127 (EBITDA/Total Assets *100) and Ratio_37 (EBITDA/Total Assets) are definitionally similar; their values should be proportional (≈ x100), unless one uses scaling and the other does not.
•	Why: Detects unit inconsistencies (percent vs raw ratio).
•	Check: Compare distributions or enforce abs(SME_Ratio_127 - 100*Ratio_37) < tolerance where both exist.

IC-22 — Moving average should be “between” current and lag when lag exists
•	Rule (conditional): MA ratios should not systematically exceed both the current and prior-year values (when both exist).
•	Why: Moving average should be an average, so it must lie between inputs unless different handling applies.
•	Gap: If the prior-year raw ratios are not stored, UK can only validate MA vs current (limited) unless lag values are also in RDS.
________________________________________
9) Bureau variables: consistency between “time since” and existence of events
IC-23 — Time-since derogatory should not exist without derog context
•	Rule (conditional): If ts_last_derogatory_dat is populated with a low number (recent), then derog-related flags (e.g. parent_company_derog_dets='Y') should be compatible where they refer to the same concept.
•	Why: Prevents contradictory encoding where “time since event” indicates an event but the flag says no event (or vice versa).
•	Note: Because some bureau variables use “blank” to mean “not retrievable”, UK should explicitly encode this semantic and adjust the check accordingly.
________________________________________
Potential data gaps to flag (for UK to confirm)
•	If there is no explicit model / submodel identifier (e.g., “GC vs SME vs CCT portfolio tag”), then several structural consistency checks (IC-19/IC-20) can only be partially implemented. UK should confirm whether Portfolio and/or Segment fully determines the applicable driver families, or whether an additional flag is needed in the RDS. We know that you have been working on segmentation variables, they should maybe added to the Dictionary.

